00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:44.800
 that starts to feel quite like a gamified.

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:46.080
 And like, you know, it's not really about

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:47.040
 the quantity of books you read,

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:48.960
 it's about like how the books you read change you,

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:50.920
 and entertain you, and inspire you, and educate you.

00:09:50.920 --> 00:09:52.280
 But it is still kind of nice

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:54.600
 to have like a little bit of gamification in that process.

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:55.720
 It's like, you know, when I go for a run,

00:09:55.720 --> 00:09:58.280
 I like to track the runs, 'cause I like to see the lines going up.

00:09:58.280 --> 00:09:59.960
 When I go to the gym, I track my workouts,

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:01.600
 even if I'm not doing progressive overload,

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:03.160
 'cause it's just nice to see the number going up.

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:04.440
 Similarly, when you're reading books

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:06.400
 and you have a way to see the number going up,

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:09.000
 it feels like you're sort of playing a game with yourself.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:10.120
 All right, the next rule is that

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:11.320
 when you are reading books,

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:13.160
 or also when you are listening to books,

00:10:13.160 --> 00:10:15.800
 it is actually totally okay to read faster

00:10:15.800 --> 00:10:17.000
 or to listen faster.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:18.600
 I realized this when I was listening

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:20.680
 to the Wheel of Time series on Audible.

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:22.720
 It's a really long series by Robert Jordan,

00:10:22.720 --> 00:10:24.560
 where the final three books are written by Brandon Sanderson.

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:26.040
 Really long series where in the middle,

00:10:26.040 --> 00:10:27.440
 it got super, super boring.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:29.800
 And that was when, back in like 2018 or something,

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:31.080
 when I was listening to the series,

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:33.040
 that was when I discovered that you could actually listen

00:10:33.040 --> 00:10:35.560
 on Audible at 1.5 XP or 2X speed.

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:36.720
 And that just like changed my life,

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:38.080
 because suddenly when the narrator

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:39.600
 is speaking at twice the speed,

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:41.200
 it actually makes the book more enjoyable,

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:43.080
 especially if it's a bit of a slog to get through.

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:44.240
 There's like three or four books

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:45.800
 like in the middle of the series that are a bit slow.

00:10:45.800 --> 00:10:47.440
 I'm so glad that I gave myself permission

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:49.160
 to listen to those at like double speed,

00:10:49.160 --> 00:10:51.080
 because then when I got through the slow bit

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:53.520
 and then the final like four books were like complete bangers,

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:55.160
 I switched those to like 1.5 XP,

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:56.240
 'cause at that point, I was kind of used

00:10:56.240 --> 00:10:57.360
 to listening to things fast.

00:10:57.360 --> 00:10:58.880
 And over time, you actually do end up

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:00.360
 training your listening speed

00:11:00.360 --> 00:11:01.880
 to the point that that actually ends up being

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:03.280
 no difference in your comprehension,

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:04.880
 listening to a book at one time speed,

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:07.040
 1.5 or two times speed or even 2.5.

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:08.600
 The more you train your listening speed

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:11.080
 and you genuinely absorb it at like a faster speed level,

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:12.560
 which means in the same amount of time,

00:11:12.560 --> 00:11:13.920
 you could just listen to more books.

00:11:13.920 --> 00:11:15.840
 Similarly, with reading, there is no law

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:17.240
 that says that you have to read

00:11:17.240 --> 00:11:18.840
 at a particular speed of reading.

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:20.600
 Some readers like to sub vocalize

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:22.040
 where it's sort of like you hear the words

00:11:22.040 --> 00:11:23.240
 in your head as you're reading.

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:24.640
 That's a fairly slow way of reading.

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:25.800
 If you want, you can train yourself

00:11:25.800 --> 00:11:27.240
 to eliminate sub vocalization

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:28.480
 and then you can read a little bit faster.

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:29.840
 And if you're able to read faster,

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:31.240
 it actually helps you get through,

00:11:31.240 --> 00:11:33.320
 especially the more boring bits of books,

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:35.840
 just quicker, which is just a nicer way of reading

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:37.800
 and a better way of being able to read more books.

00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:38.960
 At this point, some people will be like,

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:40.560
 "Well, screw you, this is terrible advice.

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:41.520
 This is toxic productivity.

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:42.800
 You should enjoy the roses and stuff."

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:44.400
 To which I would say that it's totally possible

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:45.220
 to enjoy the roses.

00:11:45.220 --> 00:11:47.120
 And sometimes the roses are even nicer

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:48.920
 when you're getting through them a little bit faster.

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:50.520
 There is no additional nobility

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:52.800
 or prestige in listening or reading a book slowly,

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:54.280
 just like there's no additional nobility

00:11:54.280 --> 00:11:55.600
 or prestige in reading it fast.

00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:56.560
 It's just like up to you,

00:11:56.560 --> 00:11:58.400
 just like all of us walk at different paces.

00:11:58.400 --> 00:11:59.720
 And there's nothing like good or bad

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:01.040
 about walking slower, walking fast.

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:02.640
 Similarly, all of us read at different paces

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:04.120
 and you can in fact train yourself

00:12:04.120 --> 00:12:05.840
 to read or listen at higher speeds,

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:08.320
 which just allows you to read more books.

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:10.480
 Next up, we have the impulse buy rule.

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:11.680
 When I first started making money

00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:13.720
 from like my side business when I was in med school,

00:12:13.720 --> 00:12:15.200
 I came across this rule, which is that

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:17.240
 whenever you see a book recommended,

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:18.500
 you should just buy the book.

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:19.960
 You should treat it like an impulse buy.

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:21.120
 You should not think about it.

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:22.240
 Obviously, if you have no money,

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:23.280
 you have to start thinking about it,

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:25.320
 but I'm sure you have way ways of acquiring books,

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:26.360
 even if you are completely broke.

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:27.800
 Like I was back when I was a teenager.

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:29.600
 And so for me, if anyone recommends me

00:12:29.600 --> 00:12:30.640
 any kind of book at all,

00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:32.080
 I will immediately open up my phone,

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:34.160
 go to Amazon or code at UK and just buy it on Kindle,

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:35.960
 or download it on Audible using that Audible Credit

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:36.920
 or whatever I feel like doing.

00:12:36.920 --> 00:12:38.200
 And I don't think twice about it.

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:39.120
 And there've been a bunch of books

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:40.960
 that I've impossible over the years where,

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:43.280
 you know, I buy the book and then maybe like two years later,

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:45.200
 I'll discover it on my Kindle and I'll start reading it.

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:47.520
 And I'll get one like life-changing idea from it

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:49.160
 that changes my life or changes my perspective

00:12:49.160 --> 00:12:50.240
 or changes my experience.

00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:51.880
 And so the return on investment of these

00:12:51.880 --> 00:12:52.800
 is absolutely huge.

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:54.080
 So the trick here is if you can,

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:56.480
 don't create friction at the point of acquisition.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:58.760
 If someone recommends you a book just like buy the book

00:12:58.760 --> 00:13:00.040
 and don't think too hard about it,

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:01.880
 and feel free to like reduce your expenses

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:03.760
 in other like less interesting areas of life,

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:05.800
 like takeaways or restaurant meals or whatever,

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:07.240
 if you need to compensate for the fact

00:13:07.240 --> 00:13:09.320
 that you're spending a bit more money on books.

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:10.160
 The final rule relates

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:11.760
 to something that James Clear talks about a lot

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:13.080
 in his book, Atomic Habits,

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:15.320
 which is the identity shift.

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:18.040
 A lot of us have the identity like we have told ourselves

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:20.600
 that I am not a reader or I struggle to read.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:23.560
 And these identity statements are very powerful

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:24.760
 and also very unhelpful

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:26.080
 if you're actually trying to read more books.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:27.560
 And so one level up is, you know,

00:13:27.560 --> 00:13:28.720
 I'm trying to read more books.

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:29.760
 I'm actively working on it.

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:31.720
 But even that is sort of implying to yourself

00:13:31.720 --> 00:13:33.520
 that you are not the sort of person who reads stuff.

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:35.720
 Whereas if you can genuinely sigh up yourself

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:37.840
 into telling yourself that I am a reader

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:39.200
 and you for example, always have a book

00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:41.080
 that you're reading, you then start to think of yourself

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:41.920
 as a reader.

00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:43.280
 And if you're a reader, then like what do you do

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:44.880
 when you've got a moment of spare time?

00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:47.000
 You don't pick up your phone and start scrolling TikTok.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:48.280
 You pick up your phone, hit Kindle

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:49.240
 and start reading on Kindle.

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:51.080
 Or you pick up a physical book and actually start reading it.

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:52.800
 And so when you have that kind of identity change

00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:54.760
 and when you always have the ability to read

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:56.280
 in any kind of moment of downtime,

00:13:56.280 --> 00:13:58.240
 that then drastically increases the amount of books

00:13:58.240 --> 00:13:59.080
 that you're able to read.

00:13:59.080 --> 00:14:01.480
 Now this whole video has been about how to read more books.

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:03.840
 But obviously reading more books isn't really the point.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:05.520
 The point is the inspiration, the motivation,

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:06.520
 the education, the learning,

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:08.920
 the entertainment that you get from the books that you read.

00:14:08.920 --> 00:14:10.400
 And if you are interested in a method

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:13.200
 for actually remembering more of the stuff that you read,

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:14.200
 there's a video over here.

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:16.000
 It's a couple of years old, but it's still very relevant.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:17.640
 This video kind of goes through my own system

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:19.640
 for how I connect to various different apps together

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:21.240
 so that I can remember everything that I read.

00:14:21.240 --> 00:14:22.840
 So if you're interested in remembering more of the things

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:24.440
 you read, you should check out that video over there.

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:26.080
 Thanks for watching. See you later.

